@Sarah (Fourth Block) 

PART 2

Although it seems as if everything related to the coronavirus is an estimate, it is hard to know whether restrictions should be listed or kept in place. With the upcoming summer in only a few months, my biggest concern is whether or not the beaches will be a massive hotspot for COVID spreading. With the endless income of tourists to our beaches in North Carolina, our state and others highly affected by tourism could potentially have the worst of it, shutting down our communities while tourists return to their “mask-free” towns. While states such as North Carolina are inclined to shut down again in the midst of summer, less popular states like North Dakota and Iowa are more likely to stay open. This affects schools from opening five days a week, small businesses staying afloat, and most importantly the elderly or those with health conditions from contracting the deadly virus. I believe decisions on lifting restrictions must be made very cautiously depending on the state’s infection and death rate, and also must be made to change easily and quickly if COVID cases start to rise.

@Eppy Camacho (3rd Block) 
Pt. 2
This scenario results in the least amount of deaths of the four graphs, 90,000, and the quickest immunity, so it is the best of the four, but that many vaccines a day may be unattainable at this time. Graph C shows that if we continue with 1.7 million shots a day, but ease up on restrictions regarding gathering, masks, and distancing, we will reach the threshold for total immunity in June and vaccine immunity in October. The earlier time of total immunity is the result of more people contracting the virus, which brings a higher amount of people recovering, but also a much higher death count of 170,000. While immunity does come faster, it is not worth how many extra deaths occur in the process. Graph D shows the possible outcome in the event of new variants, those that have wreaked havoc on other parts of the world due to their increased contagion rate. It predicts that we could reach the total immunity by July, but vaccine immunity is unknown due to the unpredictability of new variants and their resilience to the vaccine. The death prediction is a devastating 200,000 before the threshold is met, twice that of the same scenario without variants. Obviously, this is not a good outcome because so many people die, and immunity is indefinite. This virus is unpredictable and it could stray far from these predictions, or follow one of the other graphs not presented in the article.

